- "subgroups" refer to different demographic or population segments (e.g., Total 1 yr, 5 yrs, etc.);
- "immunization rates" represent the percentage of the population that has been vaccinated against specific diseases.

- 'Haemophilus influenzae type B' is a bacterium that can cause serious diseases in children, including meningitis, pneumonia, and epiglottitis;
- The immunization rate is a measure of the percentage of the population that has been vaccinated against a specific disease;
- The year 2020 is a specific point in time during which the immunization rates were recorded.

- 'Total 1 yr' refers to the immunization rate for the total population of 1-year-old children;
- The immunization rate is a measure of the percentage of the population that has been vaccinated;
- 2023 is the year in which the immunization rates were recorded.

